Part I - Prosper Loan Data¶

by Nahayo Gilbert¶

Introduction¶

Prosper is a peer-to-peer lending platform that lets borrowers access personal loans. Borrower qualifications are more accessible than many other online lenders, but rates can reach almost 36% and borrowers pay origination fees from 2.41% to 5%. Prospective borrowers can take advantage of Prospers prequalification tool to see what terms theyll qualify for without impacting their credit scores.

The data set contains 113,937 loans with 81 variables on each loan, including loan amount, borrower rate (or interest rate), current loan status, borrower income, and many others

# Getting the percentages of missing values and round down the result

percent_missing = percent_missing.round(2) 

# Concatenating the number and perecentage of missing values 
# into one dataframe and sorting it 
pd.concat([missing_values, percent_missing], axis=1, 
          keys=['missing_values', 'Percentage']).\
          sort_values(by="missing_values", ascending=False)

What is the structure of your dataset?¶

The dataset contains 83982 loans and 13 features including loan amount, borrower rate, loan status, borrower income, and many others.

What is/are the main feature(s) of interest in your dataset?¶

ProsperRating (Alpha) is the variable of interest because it is what potential investors use to decide whether to invest in the loan listing.

What features in the dataset do you think will help support your investigation into your feature(s) of interest?¶

Prosper rate is the key for the envestigation, the prosper rate will be compared to income and employement status.

Univariate Exploration¶

In [14]:
# creating a function for vertical catplots
def gt(df_prosper_loan,xvar):
    g=sb.catplot(data=df_prosper_loan, x=xvar,color = 'blue', kind='count',
           height=8 , alpha=.5, order=df_prosper_loan[xvar].value_counts().index)
    
    g.despine(left=True)
    xvar=xvar.replace("_","")
        
    g.set_axis_labels(f"Distribution of {xvar}",xvar.title())
    plt.title(f'distribution of {xvar}'.title(),weight="bold")
In [15]:
# creating a function for holizontal catplots
def gth(df_prosper_loan,yvar):
    g=sb.catplot(data=df_prosper_loan, y=yvar,color = 'blue', kind='count',
           height=10 , alpha=.6, order=df_prosper_loan[yvar].value_counts().index)
    
    g.despine(left=True)
    yvar=yvar.replace("_","")
        
    g.set_axis_labels(f"Count of {yvar}",yvar)
    plt.title(f'distribution of {yvar}'.title(),weight="bold")

Monthly payments had high effect on original amount of the loan. Stated Monthly Income and Loan Original Amount strenghtened and showed how Prosper Rating increasd whenever either amount increased.

Were there any interesting or surprising interactions between features?¶

The similarity in prosper rating levels in borrower APR among term of loan period. Borrower APR does not seem to affect prosper rating or loan term.

Conclusions¶

After comparing Prosper rating with different variable, we saw that it was indeed what is most based on to provide loan to full-time employees which the majority of them live in California state and the loan original amount starts at 5000 for most of borrowers who have high income and high percent of borrower choose Debt Consolidation when requesting loan. Moreover, the borrower APR were the same into different period of the loan.
